The '''Sussex Police Air Operations Unit''', popularly referred to by the aircrew's police net callsign, '''Hotel 900''',<ref name=h900/> was a unit of [[Sussex Police]] that provided emergency air support in the [[Sussex]] area of [[England]].<ref name=h900>{{cite web|title=H900 - The Eye in the Sky|publisher=Sussex Police|url=http://www.sussex.police.uk/features/specialistUnits/h900.asp|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref><ref name=secamb1>{{cite web|title=Ambulance service initiates radical shift in Air Ambulance deployment|date=2006-12-18|publisher=South East Coast Ambulance Service|url=http://www.secamb.nhs.uk/latest-news/july-december-2006/december-2006/ambulance-service-initiates-radical-shift-in-air-ambulance-deployment/?searchterm=hotel 900|accessdate=2009-04-29}}</ref><ref name=ukea>{{cite web|publisher=UK Emergency Aviation|title=Police Helicopters N-Z|url=http://ukemergencyaviation.co.uk/policehelicopternz.htm|accessdate=2009-03-29}}</ref> In October 2010, the unit was merged with the Air Support Units of [[Surrey Police]] and [[Hampshire Constabulary]] to form the [[South East Air Support Unit]], which officially commenced operations in April 2011.<ref name=sussex>{{cite news|title=South East Air Support Unit officially launched|url=http://www.sussex.police.uk/news-and-events/news/2011/04/01/south-east-air-support-unit-officially-launched|accessdate=4 April 2011|newspaper=Sussex Police|date=1 April 2011}}</ref>  The unit operated an [[MD Explorer]] helicopter based at [[Shoreham Airport]]<ref name=ukea/><ref>{{cite web|publisher=Shoreham Airport|title=Sussex Police Air Support Unit|url=http://www.shorehamairport.co.uk/sussexpolice.asp}}</ref> with aircrew provided by both [[Sussex Police]] and the [[South East Coast Ambulance Service]], and flew sorties at the request of police control at [[Lewes]],<ref name=h900/> or the joint air ambulance control desk at [[Coxheath]], [[Kent]].<ref name=secamb1/> 

==Operations==
Hotel 900 was crewed by a [[aviator|pilot]], a [[Sussex Police]] [[air observer]], who was a fully sworn constable (or sergeant) and a [[paramedic]] seconded from South East Coast Ambulance Service, who was also trained as an air observer.<ref name=h900/> The last helicopter was an [[MD Helicopters MD Explorer|MD-902 Explorer]] and operated from [[Shoreham Airport]].<ref name=ukea/> Operational since February 2000,<ref name=h900/> the Explorer replaced an earlier helicopter which had been in service since 1987.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Midhurst and Petworth Observer|title=Life saving service scrambled into the skies day and night in West Sussex|url=http://www.midhurstandpetworth.co.uk/news/Lifesaving-servicescrambled-into-the-skies.3939382.jp|date=03 April 2008}}</ref> The unit was available for missions between 0800 and 0130 Monday to Saturday, and 0900 to 0000 on Sundays, although out-of-hours cover was provided for serious incidents.<ref name=h900/><ref>{{cite news|publisher=Mid Sussex Times|title=New night role for Sussex Police Helicopter|url=http://www.midsussextimes.co.uk/Register.aspx?ReturnURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.midsussextimes.co.uk%2Fshoreham-news%2FNew-night-role-for-Sussex.3921538.jp|date=27 March 2008}}</ref> Hotel 900 completed nearly 1,500 sorties every year, of which almost 25% were for ambulance purposes, with the remainder consisting of police tasks, such as searching for offenders or fleeing suspects, identifying suspect or stolen vehicles, facilitating vehicle pursuits, transport of police officers, and search & rescue.<ref name=h900/>

